{
  "Which ocean floor feature is the relatively shallow, gently sloping area extending from the shoreline to the point where the slope increases sharply?": "",
  "Continental rise": "",
  "Mid-ocean ridge": "",
  "Continental shelf": "",
  "Abyssal plain": "",
  "The continental shelf is the gently sloping, submerged extension of the continent that starts at the shoreline and extends to the shelf break. It is relatively shallow compared to the deep ocean and is one of the most biologically productive regions.": "",
  "What is the deepest type of feature found on the ocean floor?": "",
  "Submarine canyon": "",
  "Ocean trench": "",
  "Seamount": "",
  "Ocean trenches are the deepest features on Earth's surface, formed at subduction zones where one tectonic plate is forced beneath another. The Mariana Trench, the deepest known trench, reaches nearly 11,000 meters below sea level.": "",
  "What technology is primarily used to map the depth of the ocean floor?": "",
  "Echo sounding (sonar)": "",
  "Satellite photography": "",
  "Radar imaging": "",
  "X-ray scanning": "",
  "Echo sounding, also known as sonar, sends sound waves toward the ocean floor and measures the time it takes for the echo to return. By knowing the speed of sound in water, scientists can calculate the depth and create detailed maps of the seafloor.": "",
  "Which ocean floor feature is a large, flat area that makes up most of the deep ocean floor?": "",
  "Guyot": "",
  "Continental slope": "",
  "Abyssal plains are vast, extremely flat areas of the deep ocean floor, typically found at depths of 3,000 to 6,000 meters. They are among the flattest places on Earth and are formed by the accumulation of fine-grained sediments that blanket the original topography.": "",
  "What is a seamount?": "",
  "A flat-topped underwater volcano": "",
  "An underwater volcanic mountain that does not reach the surface": "",
  "A canyon carved into the continental shelf": "",
  "A deep crack in the ocean floor": "",
  "A seamount is a submarine volcanic mountain rising at least 1,000 meters above the surrounding seafloor but not reaching the ocean surface. Seamounts are common features and serve as biodiversity hotspots by providing habitat for marine organisms.": "",
  "The steep descent from the edge of the continental shelf toward the deep ocean floor is called the:": "",
  "The continental slope marks the boundary between the continental shelf and the deep ocean floor. It descends steeply from the shelf break and is often cut by submarine canyons that funnel sediment down to the deep ocean.": "",
  "Mid-ocean ridges are formed by:": "",
  "Sediment accumulation over millions of years": "",
  "Erosion from deep-sea currents": "",
  "Compression at convergent boundaries": "",
  "Volcanic activity at divergent plate boundaries": "",
  "Mid-ocean ridges form where tectonic plates diverge and magma rises to fill the gap, creating new oceanic crust. This process, called seafloor spreading, produces the longest mountain chain on Earth, stretching over 65,000 kilometers.": "",
  "Which feature is found between the continental slope and the abyssal plain?": "",
  "The continental rise is the gently sloping region between the base of the continental slope and the abyssal plain. It is formed by the accumulation of sediments that have slid down the continental slope through turbidity currents and other processes.": "",
  "What is a guyot?": "",
  "A volcanic island in the open ocean": "",
  "A type of deep ocean trench": "",
  "A rift valley along a mid-ocean ridge": "",
  "A flat-topped seamount that was once above sea level": "",
  "A guyot (also called a tablemount) is a flat-topped seamount. Guyots were once volcanic islands above sea level; wave erosion flattened their peaks before the weight of the plate or changes in sea level caused them to submerge.": "",
  "Submarine canyons are primarily formed by:": "",
  "Erosion from turbidity currents and river runoff": "",
  "Coral reef growth along the continental shelf": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions on the seafloor": "",
  "Tectonic uplift of the abyssal plain": "",
  "Submarine canyons are deep, V-shaped valleys cut into the continental shelf and slope. They are primarily carved by turbidity currents—underwater landslides of sediment-laden water—and in some cases were initially carved by rivers when sea levels were lower during ice ages.": "",
  "What is bathymetry?": "",
  "The study of ocean water chemistry": "",
  "The measurement of ocean surface temperatures": "",
  "The measurement and mapping of ocean floor depths": "",
  "The study of marine organisms in the deep sea": "",
  "Bathymetry is the science of measuring and charting the depths of water bodies, particularly the ocean floor. It is the underwater equivalent of topography and uses technologies like sonar and satellite altimetry to create detailed maps of seafloor features.": "",
  "The term 'continental margin' refers to:": "",
  "The mid-ocean ridge closest to a continent": "",
  "Only the continental shelf": "",
  "The continental shelf, slope, and rise combined": "",
  "Only the abyssal plain near a continent": "",
  "The continental margin is the zone of the ocean floor between the shoreline and the abyssal plain. It includes three main subdivisions: the continental shelf, the continental slope, and the continental rise, which together form the transition from continental crust to oceanic crust.": "",
  "What does echo sounding measure?": "",
  "The time for a sound pulse to travel to the seafloor and back": "",
  "The salinity of ocean water": "",
  "The speed of ocean currents": "",
  "The temperature of the ocean floor": "",
  "Echo sounding measures the time interval between emitting a sound pulse and receiving the reflected echo from the ocean floor. Using the known speed of sound in seawater (approximately 1,500 m/s), the depth can be calculated as half the round-trip travel time multiplied by the speed of sound.": "",
  "What term describes the point where the continental shelf transitions to the steeper continental slope?": "",
  "Abyssal hill": "",
  "Rift zone": "",
  "Trench axis": "",
  "Shelf break": "",
  "The shelf break is the point where the gentle slope of the continental shelf gives way to the much steeper continental slope. It typically occurs at a depth of about 120–200 meters and marks the outer edge of the continental shelf.": "",
  "A turbidity current is best defined as:": "",
  "A deep ocean current caused by differences in salinity": "",
  "An upwelling current near the continental shelf": "",
  "A warm surface current driven by wind": "",
  "A density current of sediment-laden water flowing down a slope": "",
  "A turbidity current is a rapid, underwater flow of sediment-laden water that moves down a slope under the force of gravity. These currents can travel at high speeds, erode submarine canyons, and deposit fan-shaped accumulations of sediment on the continental rise.": "",
  "The term 'multibeam sonar' refers to:": "",
  "A single sound beam used to measure one depth point at a time": "",
  "A passive listening device to detect whale calls": "",
  "A radar system used to map continental surfaces underwater": "",
  "A sonar system that sends multiple sound beams to map a wide swath of seafloor": "",
  "Multibeam sonar emits a fan-shaped array of sound beams that cover a wide strip of the ocean floor simultaneously. This technology allows scientists to create detailed, high-resolution maps of seafloor topography much more efficiently than single-beam echo sounders.": "",
  "An abyssal hill is defined as:": "",
  "A small elevation on the deep ocean floor, typically less than 1,000 meters high": "",
  "A sediment deposit at the base of the continental slope": "",
  "A volcanic island chain over a hotspot": "",
  "A flat-topped seamount eroded by waves": "",
  "Abyssal hills are small, rounded elevations on the deep ocean floor, generally less than 1,000 meters in height. They are among the most common landforms on Earth and are typically formed by volcanic activity at mid-ocean ridges before being covered by sediment.": "",
  "What is a rift valley in the context of ocean floor features?": "",
  "A deep trench formed by one plate sliding under another": "",
  "A submarine canyon on the continental slope": "",
  "A depression at the center of a mid-ocean ridge where plates are pulling apart": "",
  "A valley on the continental shelf carved by glaciers": "",
  "A rift valley is the central depression running along the crest of a mid-ocean ridge, formed where tectonic plates are diverging. Magma rises through this rift to create new oceanic crust, making rift valleys sites of active geological processes.": "",
  "What does the term 'pelagic' refer to in relation to the ocean?": "",
  "The ocean floor surface": "",
  "The open water column, away from the seafloor and coast": "",
  "The tidal zone along the shore": "",
  "The layer of ice over polar seas": "",
  "The pelagic zone refers to the open water column of the ocean, as opposed to the benthic zone (the ocean floor). It is divided into depth zones including the epipelagic, mesopelagic, bathypelagic, abyssopelagic, and hadopelagic zones.": "",
  "The term 'benthic' refers to:": "",
  "The surface layer of the ocean": "",
  "The region around mid-ocean ridges": "",
  "The ocean floor and the organisms living on or in it": "",
  "The deepest part of an ocean trench": "",
  "The benthic zone is the ecological region at the lowest level of a water body, including the sediment surface and the layers beneath it. Benthic organisms include those living on the seafloor surface (epifauna) and those burrowing into the sediment (infauna).": "",
  "A research vessel records an echo sounding time of 4 seconds in an area where the speed of sound in seawater is 1,500 m/s. What is the approximate depth of the ocean at that location?": "",
  "6,000 meters": "",
  "750 meters": "",
  "1,500 meters": "",
  "3,000 meters": "",
  "Depth is calculated as (speed × time) / 2, because the sound must travel to the floor and back. So depth = (1,500 m/s × 4 s) / 2 = 3,000 m. Dividing by 2 accounts for the round-trip distance of the sound pulse.": "",
  "A scientist observes that sediment layers become progressively thicker moving from a mid-ocean ridge toward a continental margin. What does this pattern indicate?": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions are more common near continents": "",
  "Older seafloor near continents has had more time to accumulate sediment": "",
  "The continental crust is sinking under the weight of sediment": "",
  "Ocean currents deposit more sediment at ridges": "",
  "Seafloor spreading creates new crust at mid-ocean ridges, so the crust becomes progressively older moving away from the ridge toward the continents. Older crust has had more time to accumulate sediment, resulting in the pattern of increasing sediment thickness.": "",
  "An underwater expedition discovers a flat-topped underwater mountain covered in coral debris at a depth of 1,200 meters. The feature most likely is a:": "",
  "Fresh seamount": "",
  "A guyot is a flat-topped seamount that was once at or above sea level, where wave action eroded its peak. The presence of coral debris confirms it was once in shallow water, as reef-building corals require sunlight. Tectonic plate movement and subsidence carried it to deep water.": "",
  "A coastal city is planning to lay an undersea communications cable from one continent to another. Which ocean floor feature would present the greatest engineering challenge for the cable route?": "",
  "Mid-ocean ridge and associated rift valley": "",
  "Mid-ocean ridges present the greatest challenge due to their rugged, volcanic terrain, steep rift valleys, and active geological processes including earthquakes and hydrothermal activity. Cables must be routed carefully to avoid damage from volcanic eruptions and seismic events in these areas.": "",
  "A bathymetric map shows a narrow, deep feature running parallel to a chain of volcanic islands. This feature is most likely a(n):": "",
  "A deep, narrow feature parallel to a volcanic island chain is characteristic of an ocean trench formed at a subduction zone. As one oceanic plate subducts beneath another, the descending plate creates a trench while the melting of the plate generates the volcanic island arc.": "",
  "During a submarine dive, researchers notice the seafloor transitions from rough, pillow-shaped basalt formations to smooth, sediment-covered plains as they move away from a mid-ocean ridge. What explains this transition?": "",
  "Older crust farther from the ridge has been blanketed by accumulated sediments": "",
  "The submarine is moving toward a subduction zone": "",
  "Volcanic activity is increasing farther from the ridge": "",
  "Deep ocean currents erode the basalt into smooth surfaces": "",
  "Near mid-ocean ridges, the crust is young and volcanic features like pillow basalts are exposed. As the crust moves away from the ridge over millions of years, sediments gradually accumulate and bury the rough volcanic terrain, creating the smooth abyssal plains.": "",
  "A fisheries biologist wants to find the most productive area for commercial bottom-trawling. Based on ocean floor features, which area would likely support the most fish?": "",
  "Continental shelf at 50 meters depth": "",
  "Mid-ocean ridge at 2,500 meters depth": "",
  "Ocean trench at 8,000 meters depth": "",
  "Abyssal plain at 5,000 meters depth": "",
  "The continental shelf is the most biologically productive region because its shallow depth allows sunlight penetration, supporting photosynthesis and food webs. Nutrient runoff from land and upwelling further enrich these waters, making them prime areas for commercial fishing.": "",
  "Scientists mapping the ocean floor discover a V-shaped valley cutting across the continental shelf and down the slope to the deep ocean. They also find graded sediment deposits at the base of the slope. What feature and process does this evidence suggest?": "",
  "A rift valley formed by seafloor spreading": "",
  "An ocean trench formed by subduction": "",
  "A seamount that collapsed from erosion": "",
  "A submarine canyon carved by turbidity currents": "",
  "The V-shaped valley cutting through the shelf and slope is a submarine canyon, and the graded sediment deposits at the base of the slope are turbidite deposits. Turbidity currents—fast-moving, sediment-laden underwater flows—carve these canyons and deposit sediment fans on the continental rise.": "",
  "A new satellite-based bathymetric survey reveals a previously unknown chain of underwater mountains in the middle of an ocean basin, with a central valley running along its length. What is this feature, and how did it form?": "",
  "A continental rise formed by accumulated sediment": "",
  "An island arc formed at a convergent boundary": "",
  "A mid-ocean ridge formed at a divergent plate boundary": "",
  "A hotspot track formed as the plate moved over a stationary mantle plume": "",
  "A chain of underwater mountains with a central rift valley in the middle of an ocean basin is characteristic of a mid-ocean ridge. These ridges form at divergent boundaries where tectonic plates pull apart and magma rises to create new oceanic crust.": "",
  "An oceanographer compares two echo sounding profiles: Profile A shows a smooth, flat seafloor at 4,500 m depth, while Profile B shows rugged, mountainous terrain rising to 2,000 m depth in the center of the ocean. Which features do these profiles most likely represent?": "",
  "Profile A is a continental slope; Profile B is a seamount chain": "",
  "Profile A is an abyssal plain; Profile B is a mid-ocean ridge": "",
  "Profile A is a guyot; Profile B is a submarine canyon": "",
  "Profile A is a trench; Profile B is a continental shelf": "",
  "Profile A describes the flat, deep characteristics of an abyssal plain at typical depth. Profile B describes the rugged, elevated terrain rising from the deep ocean, which is characteristic of a mid-ocean ridge found in the center of ocean basins.": ""
}